What is LinkedHashMap?

A LinkedHashMap is a HashMap with a memory.

It stores key-value pairs just like HashMap, but also maintains a predictable order.

LinkedHashMap<Integer, String> map = new LinkedHashMap<>();
🧠 Core Idea

It combines:

⚡ HashMap (fast access)
🔗 LinkedList (order tracking)

So internally:

Hash table + Doubly Linked List
⚙️ Internal Structure

Each node looks like:

static class Entry<K,V> extends HashMap.Node<K,V> {
    Entry<K,V> before, after;
}

👉 Meaning:

Same hashing mechanism as HashMap
PLUS links to previous and next entries
🧩 Visualization
[Head] <-> [Entry1] <-> [Entry2] <-> [Entry3] <-> [Tail]

So:

HashMap → finds data fast
Linked list → keeps order intact
🔑 Key Features
1. Maintains Order

Two types:

Insertion Order (default)
Access Order (when enabled)
2. Allows null
One null key
Multiple null values
3. Not Thread-Safe

Same as HashMap.

4. Slightly Slower than HashMap

Because of extra linking overhead.

⚡ Time Complexity
Operation	Complexity
Put	O(1)
Get	O(1)
Remove	O(1)

👉 Same as HashMap (on average)

🔄 Insertion Order vs Access Order (VERY IMPORTANT)
🔹 Insertion Order (default)
LinkedHashMap<Integer, String> map = new LinkedHashMap<>();

Order stays as inserted:

1 → 2 → 3 → 4
🔹 Access Order (LRU behavior)
LinkedHashMap<Integer, String> map =
    new LinkedHashMap<>(16, 0.75f, true);

Now:

Recently accessed elements move to end

👉 Used in LRU Cache

🧰 Important Methods

Same as HashMap, plus some power moves:

🔹 Basic
map.put(1, "A");
map.get(1);
map.remove(1);
🔹 Iteration (order preserved!)
for (Map.Entry<Integer, String> e : map.entrySet()) {
    System.out.println(e.getKey());
}
🔹 removeEldestEntry (Interview Favorite)
protected boolean removeEldestEntry(Map.Entry<K,V> eldest) {
    return size() > 3;
}

👉 Automatically removes oldest entry
👉 Used to build LRU Cache

🔥 LRU Cache Example (This impresses interviewers)
class LRUCache<K,V> extends LinkedHashMap<K,V> {
    private int capacity;

    LRUCache(int capacity) {
        super(capacity, 0.75f, true);
        this.capacity = capacity;
    }

    protected boolean removeEldestEntry(Map.Entry<K,V> eldest) {
        return size() > capacity;
    }
}
⚖️ LinkedHashMap vs HashMap
Feature	HashMap	LinkedHashMap
Order	No	Yes
Performance	Faster	Slightly slower
Memory	Less	More
Use case	General	Ordered data
⚖️ LinkedHashMap vs TreeMap
Feature	LinkedHashMap	TreeMap
Order	Insertion	Sorted
Complexity	O(1)	O(log n)
Structure	Hash + List	Red-Black Tree
🚨 When to Use LinkedHashMap

Use it when:

You need fast lookup + order preservation
You’re building LRU cache
You care about iteration order
❌ When NOT to Use
Need sorted data → use TreeMap
Need max performance → use HashMap
Memory is tight → avoid it
🧠 Interview One-Liner

If they ask:

“What is LinkedHashMap?”

Say:

LinkedHashMap is a HashMap implementation that maintains insertion or access order using a doubly linked list along with hashing. It provides O(1) performance for basic operations while preserving order.